<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A very distinctive species with woody stems and a subcylindrical hypocrateriform corolla which is enclosed by a pair of showy bracteoles. As in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dumosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea dumosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the petiole and peduncle are partially fused. Although very distinct 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bracteata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. bracteata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also very variable. The leaves are usually glabrous but a pubescent form (
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Exogonium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="bracteatum" variety="pubescens">
var. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) occasionally occurs; the bracteoles and corolla are usually pink but plants with greenish bracteoles (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="bracteata" variety="viridibracta">
var. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">viridibracta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and green corollas are occasionally found.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bracteata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea bracteata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
flowers in the dry season, fide 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Chemás-Jaramillo">Chemas-Jaramillo</normalizedToken>
and Bullock (2005).
</paragraph>
